# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sentiment-analysis-nlp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] The **bag-of-words** (**BoW**) **model** is a model of text which uses an unordered collection (a "bag") of words.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] It is used in natural language processing and information retrieval (IR).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] It disregards word order (and thus most of syntax or grammar) but captures multiplicity.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] The bag-of-words model is commonly used in methods of document classification where, for example, the (frequency of) occurrence of each word is used as a feature for training a classifier.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] It has also been used for computer vision.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] An early reference to "bag of words" in a linguistic context can be found in Zellig Harris's 1954 article on *Distributional Structure*.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] The following models a text document using bag-of-words.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] Each key is the word, and each value is the number of occurrences of that word in the given text document.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] It is also what we expect from a strict *JSON object* representation.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] So, as we see in the bag algebra, the "union" of two documents in the bags-of-words representation is, formally, the disjoint union, summing the multiplicities of each element.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] The BoW representation of a text removes all word ordering.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] For example, the BoW representation of "man bites dog" and "dog bites man" are the same, so any algorithm that operates with a BoW representation of text must treat them in the same way.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] Despite this lack of syntax or grammar, BoW representation is fast and may be sufficient for simple tasks that do not require word order.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] and so the BoW representation would be insufficient to determine the detailed meaning of the document.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] Implementations of the bag-of-words model might involve using frequencies of words in a document to represent its contents.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] The frequencies can be "normalized" by the inverse of document frequency, or tf–idf.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] Additionally, for the specific purpose of classification, supervised alternatives have been developed to account for the class label of a document.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] Lastly, binary (presence/absence or 1/0) weighting is used in place of frequencies for some problems (e.g., this option is implemented in the WEKA machine learning software system).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] A common alternative to using dictionaries is the hashing trick, where words are mapped directly to indices with a hash function.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] When using a hash function, no memory is required to store a dictionary.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] In practice, hashing simplifies the implementation of bag-of-words models and improves scalability.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/bag-of-words-model] Collisions can occur when two words are hashed to the same index, but this happens infrequently and may function as a form of regularization.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] The documents to be classified may be texts, images, music, etc.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] Each kind of document possesses its special classification problems.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] When not otherwise specified, **text classification** is implied.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] Documents may be classified according to their subjects or according to other attributes (such as document type, author, printing year etc.).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] In the rest of this article only subject classification is considered.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] There are two main philosophies of subject classification of documents: the content-based approach and the request-based approach.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] Request-oriented classification may be classification that is targeted towards a particular audience or user group.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] For example, a library or a database for feminist studies may classify/index documents differently when compared to a historical library.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] It is probably better, however, to understand request-oriented classification as *policy-based classification*: The classification is done according to some ideals and reflects the purpose of the library or database doing the classification.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] In this way it is not necessarily a kind of classification or indexing based on user studies.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] Only if empirical data about use or users are applied should request-oriented classification be regarded as a user-based approach.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] Sometimes a distinction is made between assigning documents to classes ("classification") versus assigning subjects to documents ("subject indexing") but as Frederick Wilfrid Lancaster has argued, this distinction is not fruitful.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] "These terminological distinctions,” he writes, “are quite meaningless and only serve to cause confusion” (Lancaster, 2003, p.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] The view that this distinction is purely superficial is also supported by the fact that a classification system may be transformed into a thesaurus and vice versa (cf., Aitchison, 1986, 2004; Broughton, 2008; Riesthuis & Bliedung, 1991).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] Therefore, assigning a subject term to a document in an index is equivalent to assigning that document to the class of documents indexed by that term (all documents indexed or classified as X belong to the same class of documents).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/document-classification] There are several software products under various license models available.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In statistics, **naive** (sometimes **simple** or **idiot's**) **Bayes classifiers** are a family of "probabilistic classifiers" which assume that the features are conditionally independent, given the target class.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In other words, a naive Bayes model assumes the information about the class provided by each variable is unrelated to the information from the others, with no information shared between the predictors.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The highly unrealistic nature of this assumption, called the **naive independence assumption**, is what gives the classifier its name.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] These classifiers are some of the simplest Bayesian network models.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes classifiers generally perform worse than more advanced models like logistic regressions, especially at quantifying uncertainty (with naive Bayes models often producing wildly overconfident probabilities).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] However, they are highly scalable, requiring only one parameter for each feature or predictor in a learning problem.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Maximum-likelihood training can be done by evaluating a closed-form expression (simply by counting observations in each group), rather than the expensive iterative approximation algorithms required by most other models.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Despite the use of Bayes' theorem in the classifier's decision rule, naive Bayes is not (necessarily) a Bayesian method, and naive Bayes models can be fit to data using either Bayesian or frequentist methods.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes is a simple technique for constructing classifiers: models that assign class labels to problem instances, represented as vectors of feature values, where the class labels are drawn from some finite set.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] There is not a single algorithm for training such classifiers, but a family of algorithms based on a common principle: all naive Bayes classifiers assume that the value of a particular feature is independent of the value of any other feature, given the class variable.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, a fruit may be considered to be an apple if it is red, round, and about 10 cm in diameter.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] A naive Bayes classifier considers each of these features to contribute independently to the probability that this fruit is an apple, regardless of any possible correlations between the color, roundness, and diameter features.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In many practical applications, parameter estimation for naive Bayes models uses the method of maximum likelihood; in other words, one can work with the naive Bayes model without accepting Bayesian probability or using any Bayesian methods.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Despite their naive design and apparently oversimplified assumptions, naive Bayes classifiers have worked quite well in many complex real-world situations.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In 2004, an analysis of the Bayesian classification problem showed that there are sound theoretical reasons for the apparently implausible efficacy of naive Bayes classifiers.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Still, a comprehensive comparison with other classification algorithms in 2006 showed that Bayes classification is outperformed by other approaches, such as boosted trees or random forests.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] An advantage of naive Bayes is that it only requires a small amount of training data to estimate the parameters necessary for classification.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The problem with the above formulation is that if the number of features n is large or if a feature can take on a large number of values, then basing such a model on probability tables is infeasible.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The model must therefore be reformulated to make it more tractable.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In practice, there is interest only in the numerator of that fraction, because the denominator does not depend on C and the values of the features $x_{i}$ are given, so that the denominator is effectively constant.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Now the "naive" conditional independence assumptions come into play: assume that all features in $\mathbf {x}$ are mutually independent, conditional on the category $C_{k}$ .
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Often, it is only necessary to discriminate between classes.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] One is that it allows an interpretation in information theory, where log-probabilities are units of information in nats.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Another is that it avoids arithmetic underflow.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The discussion so far has derived the independent feature model, that is, the naive Bayes probability model.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The naive Bayes classifier combines this model with a decision rule.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] One common rule is to pick the hypothesis that is most probable so as to minimize the probability of misclassification; this is known as the *maximum *a posteriori** or *MAP* decision rule.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The assumptions on distributions of features are called the "event model" of the naive Bayes classifier.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] For discrete features like the ones encountered in document classification (include spam filtering), multinomial and Bernoulli distributions are popular.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] These assumptions lead to two distinct models, which are often confused.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] When dealing with continuous data, a typical assumption is that the continuous values associated with each class are distributed according to a normal (or Gaussian) distribution.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, suppose the training data contains a continuous attribute, **x**.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The data is first segmented by the class, and then the mean and variance of x is computed in each class.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Let $\mu _{k}$ be the mean of the values in x associated with class $C_{k}$ , and let $\sigma _{k}^{2}$ be the Bessel corrected variance of the values in x associated with class $C_{k}$ .
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Suppose one has collected some observation value v .
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Then, the probability *density* of v given a class $C_{k}$ , i.e., $p(x=v\mid C_{k})$ , can be computed by plugging v into the equation for a normal distribution parameterized by $\mu _{k}$ and $\sigma _{k}^{2}$ .
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Another common technique for handling continuous values is to use binning to discretize the feature values and obtain a new set of Bernoulli-distributed features.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Some literature suggests that this is required in order to use naive Bayes, but it is not true, as the discretization may throw away discriminative information.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Sometimes the distribution of class-conditional marginal densities is far from normal.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In these cases, kernel density estimation can be used for a more realistic estimate of the marginal densities of each class.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This method, which was introduced by John and Langley, can boost the accuracy of the classifier considerably.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] With a multinomial event model, samples (feature vectors) represent the frequencies with which certain events have been generated by a multinomial $(p_{1},\dots ,p_{n})$ where $p_{i}$ is the probability that event i occurs (or K such multinomials in the multiclass case).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] A feature vector $\mathbf {x} =(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ is then a histogram, with $x_{i}$ counting the number of times event i was observed in a particular instance.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This is the event model typically used for document classification, with events representing the occurrence of a word in a single document (see bag of words assumption).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Estimating the parameters in log space is advantageous since multiplying a large number of small values can lead to significant rounding error.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Applying a log transform reduces the effect of this rounding error.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] If a given class and feature value never occur together in the training data, then the frequency-based probability estimate will be zero, because the probability estimate is directly proportional to the number of occurrences of a feature's value.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This is problematic because it will wipe out all information in the other probabilities when they are multiplied.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Therefore, it is often desirable to incorporate a small-sample correction, called pseudocount, in all probability estimates such that no probability is ever set to be exactly zero.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This way of regularizing naive Bayes is called Laplace smoothing when the pseudocount is one, and Lidstone smoothing in the general case.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In the multivariate Bernoulli event model, features are independent Boolean variables (binary variables) describing inputs.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Like the multinomial model, this model is popular for document classification tasks, where binary term occurrence features are used rather than term frequencies.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This event model is especially popular for classifying short texts.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] It has the benefit of explicitly modelling the absence of terms.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Note that a naive Bayes classifier with a Bernoulli event model is not the same as a multinomial NB classifier with frequency counts truncated to one.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Re-train the model based on the *probabilities* (not the labels) predicted in the previous step.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Convergence is determined based on improvement to the model likelihood $P(D\mid \theta )$ , where $\theta$ denotes the parameters of the naive Bayes model.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This training algorithm is an instance of the more general expectation–maximization algorithm (EM): the prediction step inside the loop is the *E*-step of EM, while the re-training of naive Bayes is the *M*-step.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The algorithm is formally justified by the assumption that the data are generated by a mixture model, and the components of this mixture model are exactly the classes of the classification problem.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Despite the fact that the far-reaching independence assumptions are often inaccurate, the naive Bayes classifier has several properties that make it surprisingly useful in practice.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In particular, the decoupling of the class conditional feature distributions means that each distribution can be independently estimated as a one-dimensional distribution.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This helps alleviate problems stemming from the curse of dimensionality, such as the need for data sets that scale exponentially with the number of features.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] While naive Bayes often fails to produce a good estimate for the correct class probabilities, this may not be a requirement for many applications.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, the naive Bayes classifier will make the correct MAP decision rule classification so long as the correct class is predicted as more probable than any other class.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This is true regardless of whether the probability estimate is slightly, or even grossly inaccurate.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In this manner, the overall classifier can be robust enough to ignore serious deficiencies in its underlying naive probability model.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Other reasons for the observed success of the naive Bayes classifier are discussed in the literature cited below.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This is exactly a logistic regression classifier.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The link between the two can be seen by observing that the decision function for naive Bayes (in the binary case) can be rewritten as "predict class $C_{1}$ if the odds of $p(C_{1}\mid \mathbf {x} )$ exceed those of $p(C_{2}\mid \mathbf {x} )$ ".
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The left-hand side of this equation is the log-odds, or *logit*, the quantity predicted by the linear model that underlies logistic regression.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Since naive Bayes is also a linear model for the two "discrete" event models, it can be reparametrised as a linear function $b+\mathbf {w} ^{\top }x>0$ .
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Obtaining the probabilities is then a matter of applying the logistic function to $b+\mathbf {w} ^{\top }x$ , or in the multiclass case, the softmax function.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Discriminative classifiers have lower asymptotic error than generative ones; however, research by Ng and Jordan has shown that in some practical cases naive Bayes can outperform logistic regression because it reaches its asymptotic error faster.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Problem: classify whether a given person is a male or a female based on the measured features.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The features include height, weight, and foot size.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Although with NB classifier we treat them as independent, they are not in reality.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The following example assumes equiprobable classes so that P(male)= P(female) = 0.5.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This prior probability distribution might be based on prior knowledge of frequencies in the larger population or in the training set.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Below is a sample to be classified as male or female.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In order to classify the sample, one has to determine which posterior is greater, male or female.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] However, given the sample, the evidence is a constant and thus scales both posteriors equally.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] It therefore does not affect classification and can be ignored.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Note that a value greater than 1 is OK here – it is a probability density rather than a probability, because *height* is a continuous variable.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Since posterior numerator is greater in the female case, the prediction is that the sample is female.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Here is a worked example of naive Bayesian classification to the document classification problem.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Consider the problem of classifying documents by their content, for example into spam and non-spam e-mails.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The question that has to be answered is: "what is the probability that a given document *D* belongs to a given class *C*?" In other words, what is $p(C\mid D)\,$ ?
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Thus, the probability ratio p(*S* | *D*) / p(¬*S* | *D*) can be expressed in terms of a series of likelihood ratios.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The actual probability p(*S* | *D*) can be easily computed from log (p(*S* | *D*) / p(¬*S* | *D*)) based on the observation that p(*S* | *D*) + p(¬*S* | *D*) = 1.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] (This technique of "log-likelihood ratios" is a common technique in statistics.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Finally, the document can be classified as follows.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] It is spam if $p(S\mid D)>p(\neg S\mid D)$ (i. e., $\ln {p(S\mid D) \over p(\neg S\mid D)}>0$ ), otherwise it is not spam.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes classifiers are a popular statistical technique of e-mail filtering.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] They typically use bag-of-words features to identify email spam, an approach commonly used in text classification.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes classifiers work by correlating the use of tokens (typically words, or sometimes other things), with spam and non-spam e-mails and then using Bayes' theorem to calculate a probability that an email is or is not spam.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Variants of the basic technique have been implemented in a number of research works and commercial software products.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Many modern mail clients implement Bayesian spam filtering.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Users can also install separate email filtering programs.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Server-side email filters, such as DSPAM, Rspamd, SpamAssassin, SpamBayes, Bogofilter, and ASSP, make use of Bayesian spam filtering techniques, and the functionality is sometimes embedded within mail server software itself.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] CRM114, often cited as a Bayesian filter, is not intended to use a Bayes filter in production, but includes the ″unigram″ feature for reference.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] In the case a word has never been met during the learning phase, both the numerator and the denominator are equal to zero, both in the general formula and in the spamicity formula.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The software can decide to discard such words for which there is no information available.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] More generally, the words that were encountered only a few times during the learning phase cause a problem, because it would be an error to trust blindly the information they provide.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] A simple solution is to simply avoid taking such unreliable words into account as well.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This corrected probability is used instead of the spamicity in the combining formula.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This formula can be extended to the case where *n* is equal to zero (and where the spamicity is not defined), and evaluates in this case to $Pr(S)$ .
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] "Neutral" words like "the", "a", "some", or "is" (in English), or their equivalents in other languages, can be ignored.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] More generally, some bayesian filtering filters simply ignore all the words which have a spamicity next to 0.5, as they contribute little to a good decision.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The words taken into consideration are those whose spamicity is next to 0.0 (distinctive signs of legitimate messages), or next to 1.0 (distinctive signs of spam).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] A method can be for example to keep only those ten words, in the examined message, which have the greatest absolute value |0.5 − *pI*|.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Some software products take into account the fact that a given word appears several times in the examined message, others don't.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Some software products use *patterns* (sequences of words) instead of isolated natural languages words.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, with a "context window" of four words, they compute the spamicity of "Viagra is good for", instead of computing the spamicities of "Viagra", "is", "good", and "for".
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] This method gives more sensitivity to context and eliminates the Bayesian noise better, at the expense of a bigger database.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Depending on the implementation, Bayesian spam filtering may be susceptible to Bayesian poisoning, a technique used by spammers in an attempt to degrade the effectiveness of spam filters that rely on Bayesian filtering.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] A spammer practicing Bayesian poisoning will send out emails with large amounts of legitimate text (gathered from legitimate news or literary sources).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Spammer tactics include insertion of random innocuous words that are not normally associated with spam, thereby decreasing the email's spam score, making it more likely to slip past a Bayesian spam filter.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] However, with (for example) Paul Graham's scheme only the most significant probabilities are used, so that padding the text out with non-spam-related words does not affect the detection probability significantly.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Words that normally appear in large quantities in spam may also be transformed by spammers.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, «Viagra» would be replaced with «Viaagra» or «V!agra» in the spam message.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The recipient of the message can still read the changed words, but each of these words is met more rarely by the Bayesian filter, which hinders its learning process.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] As a general rule, this spamming technique does not work very well, because the derived words end up recognized by the filter just like the normal ones.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Another technique used to try to defeat Bayesian spam filters is to replace text with pictures, either directly included or linked.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The whole text of the message, or some part of it, is replaced with a picture where the same text is "drawn".
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] The spam filter is usually unable to analyze this picture, which would contain the sensitive words like «Viagra».
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] However, since many mail clients disable the display of linked pictures for security reasons, the spammer sending links to distant pictures might reach fewer targets.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/naive-bayes-classifier] Also, a picture's size in bytes is bigger than the equivalent text's size, so the spammer needs more bandwidth to send messages directly including pictures.
