[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Subjective and object classifier can enhance the several applications of natural language processing.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] One of the classifier's primary benefits is that it popularized the practice of data-driven decision-making processes in various industries.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] According to Liu, the applications of subjective and objective identification have been implemented in business, advertising, sports, and social science.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] It refers to determining the opinions or sentiments expressed on different features or aspects of entities, e.g., of a cell phone, a digital camera, or a bank.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] A feature or aspect is an attribute or component of an entity, e.g., the screen of a cell phone, the service for a restaurant, or the picture quality of a camera.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The advantage of feature-based sentiment analysis is the possibility to capture nuances about objects of interest.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Different features can generate different sentiment responses, for example a hotel can have a convenient location, but mediocre food.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] This problem involves several sub-problems, e.g., identifying relevant entities, extracting their features/aspects, and determining whether an opinion expressed on each feature/aspect is positive, negative or neutral.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The automatic identification of features can be performed with syntactic methods, with topic modeling, or with deep learning.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] More detailed discussions about this level of sentiment analysis can be found in Liu's work.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Emotions and sentiments are **subjective** in nature.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The **degree** of emotions/sentiments expressed in a given text at the document, sentence, or feature/aspect level—to what degree of intensity is expressed in the opinion of a document, a sentence or an entity differs on a case-to-case basis.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] However, predicting only the emotion and sentiment does not always convey complete information.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The degree or level of emotions and sentiments often plays a crucial role in understanding the exact feeling within a single class (e.g., 'good' versus 'awesome').
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Some methods leverage a stacked ensemble method for ***predicting intensity*** for emotion and sentiment by combining the outputs obtained and using deep learning models based on convolutional neural networks, long short-term memory networks and gated recurrent units.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Existing approaches to sentiment analysis can be grouped into three main categories: knowledge-based techniques, statistical methods, and hybrid approaches.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Knowledge-based techniques classify text by affect categories based on the presence of unambiguous affect words such as happy, sad, afraid, and bored.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Some knowledge bases not only list obvious affect words, but also assign arbitrary words a probable "affinity" to particular emotions.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Statistical methods leverage elements from machine learning such as latent semantic analysis, support vector machines, "bag of words", "Pointwise Mutual Information" for Semantic Orientation, semantic space models or word embedding models, and deep learning.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] More sophisticated methods try to detect the holder of a sentiment (i.e., the person who maintains that affective state) and the target (i.e., the entity about which the affect is felt).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] To mine the opinion in context and get the feature about which the speaker has opined, the grammatical relationships of words are used.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Grammatical dependency relations are obtained by deep parsing of the text.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Knowledge-based systems, on the other hand, make use of publicly available resources, to extract the semantic and affective information associated with natural language concepts.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The system can help perform affective commonsense reasoning.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Sentiment analysis can also be performed on visual content, i.e., images and videos (see Multimodal sentiment analysis).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] One of the first approaches in this direction is SentiBank utilizing an adjective noun pair representation of visual content.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] In addition, the vast majority of sentiment classification approaches rely on the bag-of-words model, which disregards context, grammar and even word order.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Approaches that analyses the sentiment based on how words compose the meaning of longer phrases have shown better result, but they incur an additional annotation overhead.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] A human analysis component is required in sentiment analysis, as automated systems are not able to analyze historical tendencies of the individual commenter, or the platform and are often classified incorrectly in their expressed sentiment.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Automation impacts approximately 23% of comments that are correctly classified by humans.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] However, humans often disagree, and it is argued that the inter-human agreement provides an upper bound that automated sentiment classifiers can eventually reach.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The accuracy of a sentiment analysis system is, in principle, how well it agrees with human judgments.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] This is usually measured by variant measures based on precision and recall over the two target categories of negative and positive texts.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] However, according to research human raters typically only agree about 80% of the time (see Inter-rater reliability).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] On the other hand, computer systems will make very different errors than human assessors, and thus the figures are not entirely comparable.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] For instance, a computer system will have trouble with negations, exaggerations, jokes, or sarcasm, which typically are easy to handle for a human reader: some errors a computer system makes will seem overly naive to a human.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] To better fit market needs, evaluation of sentiment analysis has moved to more task-based measures, formulated together with representatives from PR agencies and market research professionals.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The focus in e.g. the RepLab evaluation data set is less on the content of the text under consideration and more on the effect of the text in question on brand reputation.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Because evaluation of sentiment analysis is becoming more and more task based, each implementation needs a separate training model to get a more accurate representation of sentiment for a given data set.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] As LLM-based answer engines become more widespread, evaluation methods have expanded to include tools that track how these systems reference entities.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Illustrating emerging approaches to assessing contextual weighting and sentiment in LLM outputs include Semrushs *AI Visibility Toolkit* or *Enterprise AIO*, which analyse how entities are presented within generated responses.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The rise of social media such as blogs and social networks has fueled interest in sentiment analysis.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] With the proliferation of reviews, ratings, recommendations and other forms of online expression, online opinion has turned into a kind of virtual currency for businesses looking to market their products, identify new opportunities and manage their reputations.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] As businesses look to automate the process of filtering out the noise, understanding the conversations, identifying the relevant content and actioning it appropriately, many are now looking to the field of sentiment analysis.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Further complicating the matter, is the rise of anonymous social media platforms such as 4chan and Reddit.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] If web 2.0 was all about democratizing publishing, then the next stage of the web may well be based on democratizing data mining of all the content that is getting published.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] One step towards this aim is accomplished in research.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Several research teams in universities around the world currently focus on understanding the dynamics of sentiment in e-communities through sentiment analysis.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The problem is that most sentiment analysis algorithms use simple terms to express sentiment about a product or service.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] However, cultural factors, linguistic nuances, and differing contexts make it extremely difficult to turn a string of written text into a simple pro or con sentiment.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The fact that humans often disagree on the sentiment of text illustrates how big a task it is for computers to get this right.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The shorter the string of text, the harder it becomes.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Even though short text strings might be a problem, sentiment analysis within microblogging has shown that Twitter can be seen as a valid online indicator of political sentiment.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Tweets' political sentiment demonstrates close correspondence to parties' and politicians' political positions, indicating that the content of Twitter messages plausibly reflects the offline political landscape.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Furthermore, sentiment analysis on Twitter has also been shown to capture the public mood behind human reproduction cycles globally, as well as other problems of public-health relevance such as adverse drug reactions.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] While sentiment analysis has been popular for domains where authors express their opinion rather explicitly ("the movie is awesome"), such as social media and product reviews, only recently robust methods were devised for other domains where sentiment is strongly implicit or indirect.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] For example, in news articles - mostly due to the expected journalistic objectivity - journalists often describe actions or events rather than directly stating the polarity of a piece of information.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Earlier approaches using dictionaries or shallow machine learning features were unable to catch the "meaning between the lines", but recently researchers have proposed a deep learning based approach and dataset that is able to analyze sentiment in news articles.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Scholars have utilized sentiment analysis to analyse construction health and safety posts on Twitter (which is called X now).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The research revealed that there is a positive correlation between favorites and retweets in terms of sentiment valence.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Others have examined the impact of YouTube on the dissemination of construction health and safety knowledge.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] They investigated how emotions influence users' behaviors in terms of viewing and commenting through semantic analysis.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] In another study, positive sentiment accounted for an overwhelming figure of 85% in knowledge sharing of construction safety and health via Instagram.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] For a recommender system, sentiment analysis has been proven to be a valuable technique.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] A recommender system aims to predict the preference for an item of a target user.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Mainstream recommender systems work on explicit data set.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] For example, collaborative filtering works on the rating matrix, and content-based filtering works on the meta-data of the items.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] In many social networking services or e-commerce websites, users can provide text review, comment or feedback to the items.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] These user-generated text provide a rich source of user's sentiment opinions about numerous products and items.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Potentially, for an item, such text can reveal both the related feature/aspects of the item and the users' sentiments on each feature.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The item's feature/aspects described in the text play the same role with the meta-data in content-based filtering, but the former are more valuable for the recommender system.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] For different items with common features, a user may give different sentiments.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Also, a feature of the same item may receive different sentiments from different users.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Users' sentiments on the features can be regarded as a multi-dimensional rating score, reflecting their preference on the items.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Based on the feature/aspects and the sentiments extracted from the user-generated text, a hybrid recommender system can be constructed.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] There are two types of motivation to recommend a candidate item to a user.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The first motivation is the candidate item have numerous common features with the user's preferred items, while the second motivation is that the candidate item receives a high sentiment on its features.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] For a preferred item, it is reasonable to believe that items with the same features will have a similar function or utility.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] So, these items will also likely to be preferred by the user.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] On the other hand, for a shared feature of two candidate items, other users may give positive sentiment to one of them while giving negative sentiment to another.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Clearly, the high evaluated item should be recommended to the user.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Based on these two motivations, a combination ranking score of similarity and sentiment rating can be constructed for each candidate item.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Except for the difficulty of the sentiment analysis itself, applying sentiment analysis on reviews or feedback also faces the challenge of spam and biased reviews.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] One direction of work is focused on evaluating the helpfulness of each review.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Review or feedback poorly written is hardly helpful for recommender system.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Besides, a review can be designed to hinder sales of a target product, thus be harmful to the recommender system even it is well written.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Researchers also found that long and short forms of user-generated text should be treated differently.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] An interesting result shows that short-form reviews are sometimes more helpful than long-form, because it is easier to filter out the noise in a short-form text.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] For the long-form text, the growing length of the text does not always bring a proportionate increase in the number of features or sentiments in the text.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Lamba & Madhusudhan introduce a nascent way to cater the information needs of today's library users by repackaging the results from sentiment analysis of social media platforms like Twitter and provide it as a consolidated time-based service in different formats.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Further, they propose a new way of conducting marketing in libraries using social media mining and sentiment analysis.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Issues such as privacy, consent, and bias are crucial since sentiment analysis regularly analyzes personal data without explicit user consent.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] The potential for misinterpretation and misuse of sentiment data can significantly impact societal norms.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Furthermore, the development of ethical frameworks, as seen in projects like SEWA, where Ethical and Industrial Valorisation Advisory Boards are established, is essential for addressing these challenges.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] These boards help ensure that sentiment analysis technologies are used responsibly, especially in applications involving the recognition of human emotions and behaviors.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/sentiment-analysis] Such frameworks are vital for guiding the responsible use of sentiment analysis tools, ensuring they promote equity and respect user autonomy, and effectively address both routine and complex ethical issues.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] When classification is performed by a computer, statistical methods are normally used to develop the algorithm.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Often, the individual observations are analyzed into a set of quantifiable properties, known variously as explanatory variables or *features*.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] These properties may variously be categorical (e.g.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"), integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email) or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Other classifiers work by comparing observations to previous observations by means of a similarity or distance function.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] An algorithm that implements classification, especially in a concrete implementation, is known as a **classifier**.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] The term "classifier" sometimes also refers to the mathematical function, implemented by a classification algorithm, that maps input data to a category.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Terminology across fields is quite varied.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] In machine learning, the observations are often known as *instances*, the explanatory variables are termed *features* (grouped into a feature vector), and the possible categories to be predicted are *classes*.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Other fields may use different terminology: e.g. in community ecology, the term "classification" normally refers to cluster analysis.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Classification and clustering are examples of the more general problem of pattern recognition, which is the assignment of some sort of output value to a given input value.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] A common subclass of classification is probabilistic classification.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Algorithms of this nature use statistical inference to find the best class for a given instance.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Unlike other algorithms, which simply output a "best" class, probabilistic algorithms output a probability of the instance being a member of each of the possible classes.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] The best class is normally then selected as the one with the highest probability.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Early work on statistical classification was undertaken by Fisher, in the context of two-group problems, leading to Fisher's linear discriminant function as the rule for assigning a group to a new observation.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] This early work assumed that data-values within each of the two groups had a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] The extension of this same context to more than two groups has also been considered with a restriction imposed that the classification rule should be linear.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Unlike frequentist procedures, Bayesian classification procedures provide a natural way of taking into account any available information about the relative sizes of the different groups within the overall population.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Bayesian procedures tend to be computationally expensive and, in the days before Markov chain Monte Carlo computations were developed, approximations for Bayesian clustering rules were devised.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Some Bayesian procedures involve the calculation of group-membership probabilities: these provide a more informative outcome than a simple attribution of a single group-label to each new observation.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Classification can be thought of as two separate problems – binary classification and multiclass classification.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] In binary classification, a better understood task, only two classes are involved, whereas multiclass classification involves assigning an object to one of several classes.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Since many classification methods have been developed specifically for binary classification, multiclass classification often requires the combined use of multiple binary classifiers.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Most algorithms describe an individual instance whose category is to be predicted using a feature vector of individual, measurable properties of the instance.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Each property is termed a feature, also known in statistics as an explanatory variable (or independent variable, although features may or may not be statistically independent).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"); integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email); or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] If the instance is an image, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image; if the instance is a piece of text, the feature values might be occurrence frequencies of different words.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Some algorithms work only in terms of discrete data and require that real-valued or integer-valued data be *discretized* into groups (e.g. less than 5, between 5 and 10, or greater than 10).
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] A large number of algorithms for classification can be phrased in terms of a linear function that assigns a score to each possible category *k* by combining the feature vector of an instance with a vector of weights, using a dot product.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] The predicted category is the one with the highest score.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] In discrete choice theory, where instances represent people and categories represent choices, the score is considered the utility associated with person *i* choosing category *k*.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Algorithms with this basic setup are known as linear classifiers.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] What distinguishes them is the procedure for determining (training) the optimal weights/coefficients and the way that the score is interpreted.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Since no single form of classification is appropriate for all data sets, a large toolkit of classification algorithms has been developed.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] Choices between different possible algorithms are frequently made on the basis of quantitative evaluation of accuracy.
[src:sentiment-analysis-nlp/statistical-classification] In some of these, it is employed as a data mining procedure, while in others more detailed statistical modeling is undertaken.
